            <div facs="ia:encyclopediabrit06newyrich/page/n750/mode/1up" type="entry">
                <p><label type="entry">CURRY</label>, a name applied to a great variety of seasoned
                    dishes. In India the billowing are employed as ingredients in curries :—anise,
                    coriander, cumin, mustard, and poppy seels; allspice, almonds, asafaetida,
                    butter or ghee, cardamoms, chillies, cinnamon, cloves, cocoa-nut and cocoa-nut
                    milk and oil, cream and curds, fenugreek, the tender unripe fruit of <hi
                        rend="italic">Buchanania lancifolia,</hi> cheroonjie nuts (the produce of
                    another species, <hi rend="italic">B. latifolia),</hi> garlic and onions, <pb
                        break="no" facs="ia:encyclopediabrit06newyrich/page/n751/mode/1up"
                        xml:id="kp-eb0906-0751-0716"/> ginger, lime-juice, vinegar, the leaves of
                        <hi rend="italic">Bergera Koenigíi</hi> (the curry-leaf tree), mace,
                    mangoes, nutmeg, pepper, saffron, salt, tamarinds, and turmeric. The annexed
                    table shows the composition of four kinds of Indian curry powder :—</p>
